# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hi-c-chromatin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The chief difference between 3C-based methods is their scope.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] For example, when using PCR to detect interaction in a 3C experiment, the interactions between two specific fragments are quantified.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] In contrast, Hi-C quantifies interactions between all possible pairs of fragments simultaneously.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Deep sequencing of material produced by 3C also produces genome-wide interactions maps.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Historically, microscopy was the primary method of investigating nuclear organization, which can be dated back to 1590.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] All 3C methods start with a similar set of steps, performed on a sample of cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] First, the cell genomes are cross-linked with formaldehyde, which introduces bonds that "freeze" interactions between genomic loci.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Treatment of cells with 1-3% formaldehyde, for 10-30min at room temperature is most common, however, standardization for preventing high protein-DNA cross linking is necessary, as this may negatively affect the efficiency of restriction digestion in the subsequent step.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The genome is then cut into fragments with a restriction endonuclease.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The size of restriction fragments determines the resolution of interaction mapping.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Restriction enzymes (REs) that make cuts on 6bp recognition sequences, such as EcoR1 or HindIII, are used for this purpose, as they cut the genome once every 4000bp, giving ~ 1 million fragments in the human genome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] For more precise interaction mapping, a 4bp recognizing RE may also be used.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The next step is, proximity based ligation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] This takes place at low DNA concentrations or within intact, permeabilized nuclei in the presence of T4 DNA ligase, such that ligation between cross-linked interacting fragments is favored over ligation between fragments that are not cross-linked.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Subsequently, interacting loci are quantified by amplifying ligated junctions by PCR methods.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The chromosome conformation capture (3C) experiment quantifies interactions between a single pair of genomic loci.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] For example, 3C can be used to test a candidate promoter-enhancer interaction.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Ligated fragments are detected using PCR with known primers.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] That is why this technique requires the prior knowledge of the interacting regions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Chromosome conformation capture-on-chip (4C) (also known as circular chromosome conformation capture) captures interactions between one locus and all other genomic loci.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] It involves a second ligation step, to create self-circularized DNA fragments, which are used to perform inverse PCR.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Inverse PCR allows the known sequence to be used to amplify the unknown sequence ligated to it.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] In contrast to 3C and 5C, the 4C technique does not require the prior knowledge of both interacting chromosomal regions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Results obtained using 4C are highly reproducible with most of the interactions that are detected between regions proximal to one another.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] On a single microarray, approximately a million interactions can be analyzed.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Chromosome conformation capture carbon copy (5C) detects interactions between all restriction fragments within a given region, with this region's size typically no greater than a megabase.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] This is done by ligating universal primers to all fragments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] However, 5C has relatively low coverage.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The 5C technique overcomes the junctional problems at the intramolecular ligation step and is useful for constructing complex interactions of specific loci of interest.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] This approach is unsuitable for conducting genome-wide complex interactions since that will require millions of 5C primers to be used.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Hi-C uses high-throughput sequencing to find the nucleotide sequence of fragments and uses paired end sequencing, which retrieves a short sequence from each end of each ligated fragment.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] As such, for a given ligated fragment, the two sequences obtained should represent two different restriction fragments that were ligated together in the proximity based ligation step.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The pair of sequences are individually aligned to the genome, thus determining the fragments involved in that ligation event.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Hence, all possible pairwise interactions between fragments are tested.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] A number of methods use oligonucleotide capture to enrich 3C and Hi-C libraries for specific loci of interest.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] These methods include Capture-C, NG Capture-C, Capture-3C, HiCap, Capture Hi-C. and Micro Capture-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] These methods are able to produce higher resolution and sensitivity than 4C based methods, Micro Capture-C provides the highest resolution of the available 3C techniques and it is possible to generate base pair resolution data.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Single-cell adaptations of these methods, such as ChIP-seq and Hi-C can be used to investigate the interactions occurring in individual cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] A number of methods sequence multiple ligation junctions simultaneously to detect higher-order structures where multiple regions of chromatin may be interacting.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] These methods include Tri-C, 3way 4C/C-walks, multi-contact 4C (MC-4C), and hiPore-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] ChIP-loop combines 3C with ChIP-seq to detect interactions between two loci of interest mediated by a protein of interest.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The ChIP-loop may be useful in identifying long-range *cis*-interactions and *trans* interaction mediated through proteins since frequent DNA collisions will not occur.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] ChIA-PET combines Hi-C with ChIP-seq to detect all interactions mediated by a protein of interest.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] HiChIP was designed to allow similar analysis as ChIA-PET with less input material.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The endonuclease used in these assays is important.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] This is because data are only generated from the endonuclease cut sites the choice of enzyme determines the maximum potential resolution of the assay.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] 3C methods initially used restriction endonucleases which cut with specific recognition sequences.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The early 3C and Hi-C used 6-cutter restriction enzymes, such as HindIII, which cut approximately every 4096 base pairs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Subsequently, 4-cutter enzymes such as DpnII were used, particularly in 4C and Capture-C assays and these were later adopted widely in Hi-C methods.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] These cut approximately every 254 base pairs and afford a 16-fold potential increase in resolution.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Subsequently, non-sequence specific endonucleases have been introduced which allow an increase in potential resolution, providing deep enough datasets can be generated.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Micrococcal nuclease based 3C was first developed by the Rando lab in yeast and has subsequently been adapted for mammalian cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] These allow a substantial increase in resolution and even potentially allow contacts between individual DNA binding proteins to be resolved.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] 3C methods have led to a number of biological insights, including the discovery of new structural features of chromosomes, the cataloguing of chromatin loops, and increased understanding of transcriptional regulation mechanisms (the disruption of which can lead to disease).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] 3C methods have demonstrated the importance of spatial proximity of regulatory elements to the genes that they regulate.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] For example, in tissues that express globin genes, the β-globin locus control region forms a loop with these genes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] This loop is not found in tissues where the gene is not expressed.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] This technology has further aided the genetic and epigenetic study of chromosomes both in model organisms and in humans.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] These methods have revealed large-scale organization of the genome into topologically associating domains (TADs), which correlate with epigenetic markers.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Some TADs are transcriptionally active, while others are repressed.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Many TADs have been found in D. melanogaster, mouse and human.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Moreover, CTCF and cohesin play important roles in determining TADs and enhancer-promoter interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The result shows that the orientation of CTCF binding motifs in an enhancer-promoter loop should be facing to each other in order for the enhancer to find its correct target.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] There are several diseases caused by defects in promoter-enhancer interactions, which are reviewed in this paper.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Beta thalassemia is a certain type of blood disorder caused by a deletion of LCR enhancer element.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Holoprosencephaly is cephalic disorder caused by a mutation in the SBE2 enhancer element, which in turn weakened the production of SHH gene.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] PPD2 (polydactyly of a triphalangeal thumb) is caused by a mutation of ZRS enhancer, which in turn strengthened the production of SHH gene.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Adenocarcinoma of the lung can be caused by a duplication of enhancer element for MYC gene.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] T-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia is caused by an introduction of a new enhancer.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The different 3C-style experiments produce data with very different structures and statistical properties.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] As such, specific analysis packages exist for each experiment type.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Hi-C data is often used to analyze genome-wide chromatin organization, such as topologically associating domains (TADs), linearly contiguous regions of the genome that are associated in 3-D space.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Several algorithms have been developed to identify TADs from Hi-C data.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Hi-C and its subsequent analyses are evolving.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Fit-Hi-C is a method based on a discrete binning approach with modifications of adding distance of interaction (initial spline fitting, aka spline-1) and refining the null model (spline-2).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The result of Fit-Hi-C is a list of pairwise intra-chromosomal interactions with their p-values and q-values.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The 3-D organization of the genome can also be analyzed via eigendecomposition of the contact matrix.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Each eigenvector corresponds to a set of loci, which are not necessarily linearly contiguous, that share structural features.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] A significant confounding factor in 3C technologies is the frequent non-specific interactions between genomic loci that occur due to random polymer behavior.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] An interaction between two loci must be confirmed as specific through statistical significance testing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] There are two major ways of normalizing raw Hi-C contact heat maps.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The first way is to assume equal visibility, meaning there is an equal chance for each chromosomal position to have an interaction.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Therefore, the true signal of a Hi-C contact map should be a balanced matrix (Balanced matrix has constant row sums and column sums).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] An example of algorithms that assumes equal visibility is Sinkhorn-Knopp algorithm, which scales the raw Hi-C contact map into a balanced matrix.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The other way is to assume there is a bias associated with each chromosomal position.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The contact map value at each coordinate will be the true signal at that position times bias associated with the two contact positions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] An example of algorithms that aim to solve this model of bias is iterative correction, which iteratively regressed out row and column bias from the raw Hi-C contact map.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] There are a number of software tools available for analysis of Hi-C data.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] DNA motifs are specific short DNA sequences, often 8-20 nucleotides in length which are statistically overrepresented in a set of sequences with a common biological function.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Currently, regulatory motifs on the long-range chromatin interactions have not been studied extensively.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Several studies have focused on elucidating the impact of DNA motifs in promoter-enhancer interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Bailey et al. has identified that ZNF143 motif in the promoter regions provides sequence specificity for promoter-enhancer interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Mutation of ZNF143 motif decreased the frequency of promoter-enhancer interactions suggesting that ZNF143 is a novel chromatin-looping factor.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] For genome-scale motif analysis, in 2016, Wong et al. reported a list of 19,491 DNA motif pairs for K562 cell line on the promoter-enhancer interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] As a result, they proposed that motif pairing multiplicity (number of motifs that are paired with a given motif) is linked to interaction distance and regulatory region type.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] In the next year, Wong published another article reporting 18,879 motif pairs in 6 human cell lines.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] A novel contribution of this work is MotifHyades, a motif discovery tool that can be directly applied to paired sequences.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] The 3C-based techniques can provide insights into the chromosomal rearrangements in the cancer genomes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/chromosome-conformation-capture] Moreover, they can show changes of spatial proximity for regulatory elements and their target genes, which bring deeper understanding of the structural and functional basis of the genome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CCCTC-Binding factor or CTCF was initially discovered as a negative regulator of the chicken c-myc gene.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] This protein was found to be binding to three regularly spaced repeats of the core sequence CCCTC and thus was named CCCTC binding factor.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Although CTCF was initially discovered as a transcription factor, more recent research has revealed its central role in regulating the 3D chromatin architecture.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] The role of CTCF in 3D chromatin architecture arises from its participation in the process of loop extrusion.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Loop extrusion is a mechanism by which SMC complexes such as cohesin translocate along chromatin and progressively enlarge DNA loops.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] In higher eukaryotes, CTCF acts as a directional barrier to extrusion: when cohesin encounters a DNA-bound CTCF oriented in the correct direction, extrusion halts.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Through this mechanism, CTCF helps form chromatin loops between specific genomic elements, and establish the boundaries of topologically associating domains (TADs), thereby influencing long-range regulation of gene expression.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF binding has also been both shown to promote and repress gene expression.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] It is unknown whether CTCF affects gene expression solely through its looping activity, or if it has some other, unknown, activity.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] In addition to demarcating TADs, CTCF mediates promoter–enhancer interactions within a TAD.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] It is likely that CTCF helps to bridge the transcription factors bound to transcription start sites and RNA polymerase.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] This model has been suggested in pioneering works on the beta-globin locus.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF is conserved across eumetazoans, including cnidarians and bilaterians, but is absent from earlier-branching animals such as sponges and from non-animal eukaryotes, suggesting that it arose in the common ancestor of eumetazoans approximately 600–700 million years ago.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] The binding of CTCF has been shown to have many effects, which are enumerated below.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] In each case, it is unknown if CTCF directly evokes the outcome or if it does so indirectly (in particular through its looping role).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] The protein CTCF plays a heavy role in repressing the insulin-like growth factor 2 gene, by binding to the H-19 imprinting control region (ICR) along with differentially-methylated region-1 (DMR1) and MAR3.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Binding of targeting sequence elements by CTCF can block the interaction between enhancers and promoters, therefore limiting the activity of enhancers to certain functional domains.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Besides acting as enhancer blocking, CTCF can also act as a chromatin barrier by preventing the spread of heterochromatin structures.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF plays a central role in organizing three-dimensional chromatin structure in eumetazoans by regulating the process of loop extrusion.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] In this mechanism, cohesin complexes translocate along chromatin and progressively enlarge DNA loops until they encounter DNA-bound CTCF.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] The role of CTCF as an extrusion barrier, and its function in establishing topologically associating domain (TAD) boundaries, was first proposed theoretically and later supported by experiments showing that depletion of CTCF disrupts these domain boundaries.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] The barrier activity of CTCF is directional.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Cohesin extrusion is halted when cohesin encounters a CTCF site in the appropriate orientation, which is determined by the orientation of the CTCF motif in the genome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Structural and biochemical studies indicate that this directionality arises because the N-terminal region of CTCF interacts with cohesin and blocks its translocation along DNA.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Computer simulations suggests that when cohesin is halted at a CTCF site, it should continue extruding DNA from the opposite side.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] This mechanism contributes to the formation of topologically associating domains (TADs) and other chromatin loops observed in genome-wide chromosome conformation capture experiments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Recent studies showed that such CTCF-CTCF loops are rather transient.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Stable CTCF-CTCF loops are not essential for formation of TADs, which instead arise due to continuous loop extrusion.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Through this barrier function, CTCF can both facilitate and restrict genomic interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF sites positioned near regulatory elements can promote loop formation between them, whereas CTCF sites located between genomic regions can prevent their interaction and act as insulators.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] In addition to its role as an extrusion barrier, some studies suggest that CTCF may also form homodimers, which may contribute to chromatin loop stabilization.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF binding has been shown to influence mRNA splicing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF binds to the consensus sequence RCCASNAGRKGGCRS (in IUPAC notation).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] This sequence is defined by 11 zinc finger motifs in its structure.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF's binding is disrupted by CpG methylation of the DNA it binds to.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] On the other hand, CTCF binding may set boundaries for the spreading of DNA methylation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] In recent studies, CTCF binding loss is reported to increase localized CpG methylation, which reflected another epigenetic remodeling role of CTCF in human genome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF binds to an average of about 55,000 DNA sites in 19 diverse cell types (12 normal and 7 immortal) and in total 77,811 distinct binding sites across all 19 cell types.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF's ability to bind to multiple sequences through the usage of various combinations of its zinc fingers earned it the status of a "multivalent protein".
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] More than 30,000 CTCF binding sites have been characterized.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] The human genome contains anywhere between 15,000 and 40,000 CTCF binding sites depending on cell type, suggesting a widespread role for CTCF in gene regulation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] In addition CTCF binding sites act as nucleosome positioning anchors so that, when used to align various genomic signals, multiple flanking nucleosomes can be readily identified.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] On the other hand, high-resolution nucleosome mapping studies have demonstrated that the differences of CTCF binding between cell types may be attributed to the differences in nucleosome locations.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] Methylation loss at CTCF-binding site of some genes has been found to be related to human diseases, including male infertility.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF binds to itself to form homodimers.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF has also been shown to interact with Y box binding protein 1.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF also co-localizes with cohesin, which extrudes chromatin loops by actively translocating one or two DNA strands through its ring-shaped structure, until it meets CTCF in a proper orientation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/ctcf] CTCF is also known to interact with chromatin remodellers such as Chd4 and Snf2h (SMARCA5).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Similar to the classic 3C technique, Hi-C measures the frequency (as an average over a cell population) at which two DNA fragments physically associate in 3D space, linking chromosomal structure directly to the genomic sequence.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The general procedure of Hi-C involves first crosslinking chromatin material using formaldehyde.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Then, the chromatin is solubilized and fragmented, and interacting loci are re-ligated together to create a genomic library of chimeric DNA molecules.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The relative abundance of these chimeras, or ligation products, is correlated to the probability that the respective chromatin fragments interact in 3D space across the cell population.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] As a result, biotin-marked ligation junctions can be purified more efficiently by streptavidin-coated magnetic beads, and chromatin interaction data can be obtained by direct sequencing of the Hi-C library.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In recent years, Hi-C has found its application in a wide variety of biological fields, including cell growth and division, transcription regulation, fate determination, development, autoimmune disease, and genome evolution.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] By combining Hi-C data with other datasets such as genome-wide maps of chromatin modifications and gene expression profiles, the functional roles of chromatin conformation in genome regulation and stability can also be delineated.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] At its inception, Hi-C was a low-resolution, high-noise technology that was only capable of describing chromatin interaction regions within a bin size of 1 million base pairs (Mb).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The Hi-C library also required several days to construct, and the datasets themselves were low in both output and reproducibility.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Nevertheless, Hi-C data offered new insights for chromatin conformation as well as nuclear and genomic architectures, and these prospects motivated scientists to put efforts to modify the technique over the past decade.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Between 2012 and 2015, several modifications to the Hi-C protocol have taken place, with 4-cutter digestion or adapted deeper sequencing depth to obtain higher resolution.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The use of restriction endonucleases that cut more frequently, or DNaseI and Micrococcal nucleases also significantly increased the resolution of the method.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] More recently (2017), Belaghzal et al. described a Hi-C 2.0 protocol that was able to achieve kilobase (kb) resolution.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The key adaptation to the base protocol was the removal of the SDS solubilization step after digestion to preserve nuclear structure and prevent random ligation between fragmented chromatin by ligation within the intact nuclei, which formed the basis of in situ Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In 2021, Hi-C 3.0 was described by Lafontaine et al., with higher resolution achieved by enhancing crosslinking with formaldehyde followed by disuccinimidyl glutarate (DSG).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] While formaldehyde captures the amino and imino groups of both proteins and DNA, the NHS-esters in DSG react with primary amines on proteins and can capture amine-amine interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] These updates to the base protocol allowed the scientists to look at more detailed conformational structures such as chromosomal compartment and topologically associating domains (TADs), as well as high-resolution conformational features such as DNA loops.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] To date, a variety of derivatives of Hi-C have already emerged, including in situ Hi-C, low Hi-C, SAFE Hi-C, and Micro-C, with distinctive features related to different aspects of standard Hi-C, but the basic principle has remained the same.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The outline of the classical Hi-C workflow is as follows: cells are cross-linked with formaldehyde; chromatin is digested with a restriction enzyme that generates a 5' overhang; the 5' overhang is filled with biotinylated bases and the resulting blunt-ended DNA is ligated.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The ligation products, with biotin at the junction, are selected for using streptavidin and further processed to prepare a library ready for subsequent sequencing efforts.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The pairwise interactions that Hi-C can capture across the genome are immense and so it is important to analyze an appropriately large sample size, in order to capture unique interactions that may only be observed in a minority of the general population.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] To obtain a high complexity library of ligation products that will ensure high resolution and depth of data, a sample of 20–25 million cells is required as input for Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Primary human samples, which may be available only in fewer cell numbers, could be used for standard Hi-C library preparation with as low as 1–5 million cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] However, using such a low input of cells may be associated with low library complexity which results in a high percentage of duplicate reads during library preparation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Standard Hi-C gives data on pairwise interactions at the resolution of 1 to 10 Mb, requires high sequencing depth and the protocol takes around 7 days to complete.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Cell and nuclear membranes are highly permeable to formaldehyde.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Formaldehyde cross-linking is frequently employed for the detection and quantification of DNA-protein and protein-protein interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Of interest in the context of Hi-C, and all 3C-based methods, is the ability of formaldehyde to capture cis chromosomal interactions between distal segments of chromatin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] It does so by forming covalent links between spatially adjacent chromatin segments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Formaldehyde can react with macromolecules in two steps: first it reacts with a nucleophilic group on a DNA base for example, and forms a methylol adduct, which is then converted to a Schiff base.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In the second step, the Schiff base, which can decompose rapidly, forms a methylene bridge with another functional group on another molecule.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] It can also make this methylene bridge with a small molecule in solution such as glycine, which is used in excess to quench formaldehyde in Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Quenchers can typically exert an effect on formaldehyde from outside the cell.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] A key feature of this two-step formaldehyde crosslinking reaction is that all the reactions are reversible, which is vital for chromatin capture.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Crosslinking is a pivotal step of the chromatin capture workflow as the functional readout of the technique is the frequency at which two genomic regions are crosslinked to each other.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Thus, the standardization of this step is important and for that, one must consider potential sources of variation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Presence of serum, which contains a high concentration of protein, in culture media can decrease the effective concentration of formaldehyde available for chromatin crosslinking, by sequestering it in the culture media.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Therefore, in cases where serum is used in culture, it should be removed for the crosslinking step.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The nature of cells, i.e., whether they are suspension or adherent, is also a pertinent consideration for the crosslinking step.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Adherent cells bind to surfaces with the help of molecular mechanisms of cytoskeletons.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] It has been shown that there is a link between cytoskeleton-maintained nuclear and cellular morphology which, if altered, may negatively impact global nuclear organization.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Adherent cells therefore, should be crosslinked while still attached to their culture surface.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Cells are lysed on ice with cold hypotonic buffer containing sodium chloride, Tris-HCl at pH 8.0, and non-ionic detergent IGEPAL CA-630, supplemented with protease inhibitors.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The protease inhibitors and incubation on ice help preserve the integrity of crosslinked chromatin complexes from endogenous proteases.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The lysis step helps to release the nucleic material from the cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Following cell lysis, chromatin is solubilized with dilute SDS in order to remove proteins that have not been crosslinked and to open chromatin and make it more accessible for subsequent restriction endonuclease-mediated digestion.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] If the incubation with SDS exceeds the recommended 10 minutes, the formaldehyde crosslinks can be reversed and so the incubation with SDS must be immediately followed by an incubation on ice.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] A non-ionic detergent called Triton X-100 is used to quench SDS in order to prevent enzyme denaturation in the next step.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Any restriction enzyme that generates a 5' overhang, such as HindIII can be used to digest the now accessible chromatin overnight.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This 5' overhang provides the template required by the Klenow fragment of DNA Polymerase I to add biotinylated CTP or ATP to the digested ends of chromatin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This step allows for the selection of Hi-C ligation products for library preparation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] A dilution ligation is performed on DNA fragments that are still crosslinked to one another in order to favor the intramolecular ligation of fragments within the same chromatin complex instead of ligation events between fragments across different complexes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Since this ligation step occurs between blunt-ended DNA fragments (since the sticky ends have been filled in with biotin-labeled bases), the reaction is allowed to go on for up to 4 hours to make up for its inherent inefficiency.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] As a result of proximity ligation, the terminal HindIII sites are lost and an NheI site is generated.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The biotin-labeled ligation products can be purified using phenol-chloroform DNA extraction.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] To remove any fragments with biotin-labeled ends that have not been ligated, T4 DNA Polymerase with 3' to 5' exonuclease activity is used to remove nucleotides from the ends of such fragments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This step ensures that none of these unligated fragments are selected for library preparation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The reaction is stopped with EDTA and the DNA is purified once again using phenol-chloroform DNA extraction.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The ideal size of DNA fragments for the sequencing library depends on the sequencing platform that will be used.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] DNA can first be sheared to fragments around 300–500 bp long using sonication.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Fragments of this size are suitable for high-throughput sequencing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Following sonication, fragments can be size selected using AMPure XP beads from Beckman Coulter to obtain ligation products with a size distribution between 150 and 300 bp.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This is the optimal fragment size window for HiSeq cluster formation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] DNA shearing causes asymmetric DNA breaks and must be repaired before biotin pulldown and sequencing adaptor ligation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This is achieved by using a combination of enzymes that fill in 5' overhangs, and add 5' phosphate groups and adenylate to the 3' ends of fragments to allow for ligation of sequencing adaptors.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Using an excess of streptavdin beads, such as the My-One C1 streptavidin bead solution from Dynabeads, biotinylated Hi-C ligation products can be pulled-down and enriched for.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Ligation of the Illumina paired-end adapters is performed while the DNA fragments are bound to the streptavidin beads.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Adsorption to the beads increases efficiency of the ligation of these blunt-ended DNA fragments to the adaptors, as it decreases their mobility.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] After the ligation of the adaptors is complete, PCR amplification of the library is performed.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The PCR step can introduce high number of duplicates in a low complexity Hi-C ligation product sample as a result of over-amplification.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This results in very few interactions being captured and oftentimes, this is because the input sample size had a low amount of cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] It is important to titrate the number of cycles required to get at least 50 ng of Hi-C library DNA for sequencing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Fewer the cycle number, the better so that there are no PCR artifacts (such as off-target amplicons, non-specificity, etc.).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The ideal range of PCR cycles is 9–15 and it is more ideal to pool multiple PCR reactions to get enough DNA for sequencing, than to increase the number of cycles for one PCR reaction.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The PCR products are purified again using AMPure beads to remove primer dimers and then quantified before being sequenced.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Regions of chromatin that interact with each other are then identified by paired-end sequencing of the biotinylated, ligated products.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Any platform that can allow for the ligated fragments to be sequenced across the NheI junction (Roche 454) or by paired-end or mate-paired reads (Illumina GA and HiSeq platforms) would be suitable for Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Before high-throughput sequencing, the quality of the library should be verified using Sanger sequencing, wherein the long sequencing read will read through the biotin junction.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Thirty-six or 50 bp reads are sufficient to identify most chromatin interacting pairs using Illumina paired-end sequencing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Since the average size of fragments in the library is 250 bp, 50bp paired-end reads have been found to be optimum for Hi-C library sequencing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] There are several pressure points throughout the workflow of Hi-C sample preparation that are well documented and reported.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] DNA at various stages can be run on 0.8% agarose gels to assay the size distribution of fragments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This is particularly important after shearing of size selection steps.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Degradation of DNA can also be monitored as smears appearing as a result under low molecular weight products on gels.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Degradation can occur due to not adding sufficient protease inhibitors during lysis, endogenous nuclease activity or thermal degradation due to incorrect icing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] 3C PCR reactions can be performed to test for the formation of proximity ligation products.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Standard Hi-C has a high input cell number cost, requires deep sequencing, generates low-resolution data, and suffers from formation of redundant molecules that contribute to low complexity libraries when cell numbers are low.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] To combat these issues in order to be able to apply this technique in contexts where cell number is a limiting factor, for example, with primary human cell work, several Hi-C variants have been developed since the first conceptualization of Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The four main classes under which Hi-C variants fall under are: dilution ligation, in situ ligation, single cell, and low noise improvement systems.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Standard Hi-C is a type of dilution ligation and other dilution ligation include DNase Hi-C and Capture Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In contrast to standard and Capture Hi-C, DNase Hi-C requires only 2–5 million cells as input, uses DNaseI for chromatin fragmentation and employs an in-gel dilution proximity ligation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The use of DNaseI has been shown to greatly improve efficiency and resolution of Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Capture Hi-C is a genome-wide assaying technique to look at chromatin interactions of specific loci using a hybridization-based capture of targeted genomic regions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] It was first developed by Mifsud et al. to map long-range promoter contacts in human cells by generating a biotinylated RNA bait library that targeted 21,841 promoter regions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] These variants, in addition to others (described below), represent modifications to the foundational technique of standard Hi-C and address and alleviate one or more limitations of the original method.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In situ Hi-C combines standard Hi-C with nuclear ligation assay, i.e., proximity ligation performed in intact nuclei.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The protocol is similar to standard Hi-C in terms of the basic workflow outline but differs in other ways.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In situ Hi-C requires 2 to 5 million cells compared to the ideal 20 to 25 million required for standard Hi-C and it requires only 3 days to complete the protocol versus 7 days for standard Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Furthermore, proximity ligation does not take place in solution like in standard Hi-C, decreasing the frequency of random, biologically irrelevant contacts and ligations, as indicated by the lower frequency of mitochondrial and nuclear DNA contacts in captured biotinylated DNA.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This is achieved by leaving the nuclei intact for the ligation step.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Cells are still lysed with a buffer containing Tris-HCl at pH 8.0, sodium chloride, and the detergent IGEPAL CA630 before ligation, but instead of homogenization of the cell lysate, cell nuclei are pelleted after initial lysis to degrade the cell membrane.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] After proximity ligation is complete, cell nuclei are incubated for at least 1.5 hours at 68 degrees Celsius to permeabilize the nuclear membrane and release its nuclear contents.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The resolution that can be achieved with in situ Hi-C can be up to 950 to 1000 bp compared to the 1 to 10 Mb resolution of standard Hi-C and the 100 kb resolution of DNase Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Data between replicates for in situ Hi-C is consistent and highly reproducible, with very less background noise and demonstrating clear chromatin interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] It also requires an extremely high sequencing depth of around 5 billion paired-end reads per sample to achieve the resolution of data described by Rao et al.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Several techniques that have adapted the concept of in situ Hi-C exist, including Sis Hi-C, OCEAN-C and in situ capture Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Described below are two of the most prominent in situ Hi-C based techniques.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Low-C is an in situ Hi-C protocol adapted for use on low cell numbers, which is particularly useful in contexts where cell number is a limiting agent, for example, in primary human cell culture.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This method makes use of minor changes, including volumes and concentrations used and the timing and order of certain experimental steps to allow for the generation of high-quality Hi-C libraries from cell numbers as low as 1000 cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Despite the potential of generating usable and high resolution data with as few as 1000 cells, Diaz et al. still recommend using at least 1 to 2 million cells if feasible, or if not a minimum of 500 K cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Library quality was first assessed on the Illumina MiSeq (2x84 np paired-end reads) platform and once passed quality control criteria (including low PCR duplicates), the library was sequenced on Illumina NextSeq (2x80 bp paired-end).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] SAFE Hi-C, or simplified, fast, and economically efficient Hi-C, generates sufficient ligated fragments without amplification for high-throughput sequencing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In situ Hi-C data that has been published indicates that amplification (at the PCR step for library preparation) introduces distance-dependent amplification bias, which results in a higher noise to signal ratio against genomic distance.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] SAFE Hi-C was successfully used to generate an amplification-free, in situ Hi-C ligation library from as low as 250 thousand K562 cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Ligation fragments are anywhere between 200 and 500 bp long, with an average at about 370 bp.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] All ligation product libraries were sequenced using the Illumina HiSeq platform (2x150 bp paired-end reads).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Although SAFE Hi-C can be used for a cell input as low as 250 thousand, Niu et al. recommend using 1 to 2 million cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Samples produce enough ligates to be sequenced on one-fourth of a lane.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] SAFE Hi-C has been demonstrated to increase library complexity due to the removal of PCR duplicates which lower the overall percentage of unique paired reads.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Overall, SAFE Hi-C preserves the integrity of chromosomal interactions while also reducing the need to have high sequencing depth and saving overall cost and labor.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Micro-C is a version of Hi-C that includes a micrococcal nuclease (MNase) digestion step to look at interactions between pairs of nucleosomes, thus enabling resolution of sub-genomic TAD structures at the 1 to 100 nucleosome scale.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] It was first developed for use in yeast and was shown to conserve the structural data obtained from a standard Hi-C but with greater signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] When used with human embryonic stem cells and fibroblasts, 2.6 to 4.5 billion uniquely mapped reads were obtained per sample.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Hsieh et al. analyzed 2.64 billion reads from mouse embryonic stem cells and demonstrated that there was increased power for detecting short-range interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Hi-C has also been adapted for use with single cells but these techniques require high levels of expertise to perform and are plagued with issues such as low data quality, coverage, and resolution.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] **Epigenetic Insights:** By identifying preserved chromatin interactions, PaleoHi-C provides a unique window into the regulation of genes in ancient organisms.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Studies have demonstrated that chromatin organization, including Barr bodies representing inactive X chromosomes, can remain intact in ancient nuclei.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] **Evolutionary Studies:** The technique aids in understanding how genome organization has evolved over time and across species.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The adaptation of Hi-C for ancient DNA has transformed the field of paleogenomics, allowing for detailed studies of extinct species at a molecular level.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] By preserving and analyzing chromatin interactions, PaleoHi-C sheds light on genome structure, evolution, and adaptation in ancient ecosystems.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] PaleoHi-C is constrained by the availability of well-preserved samples and the inherent challenges of working with highly degraded DNA.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] However, advances in sequencing technologies and computational methods continue to expand its potential applications.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The chimeric DNA ligation products generated by Hi-C represent pairwise chromatin interactions or physical 3D contacts within the nucleus, and can be analyzed by a variety of downstream approaches.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Briefly, deep sequencing data is used to build unbiased genome-wide chromatin interaction maps.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Then several different methods can be employed to analyze these maps to identify chromosomal structural patterns and their biological interpretations.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Many of these data analysis approaches also apply to 3C-sequencing or other equivalent data.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Hi-C data produced by deep sequencing is in the form of a traditional FASTQ file, and the reads can be aligned to the genome of interest using sequence alignment software (e.g.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Because Hi-C ligation products may span hundreds of megabases and may bridge loci on different chromosomes, Hi-C read alignment is often chimeric in the sense that different parts of a read may be aligned to loci distant apart, possibly in different orientations.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Long-read aligners (e.g. minimap2) often support chimeric alignment and can be directly applied to long-read Hi-C data.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Short-read Hi-C alignment is more challenging.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Notably, Hi-C generates ligation junctions of varying sizes, but the exact position of the ligation site is not measured.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] To circumvent this problem, iterative mapping is used to avoid the search for the junction site before being able to split the reads into two and mapping them separately to identify the interaction pairs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The idea behind iterative mapping is to map as short a sequence as possible to ensure unique identification of interaction pairs before reaching the junction site.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] As a result, 25-bp long reads starting from the 5' end are mapped to the genome at first, and reads that do not uniquely map to a single loci are extended by an additional 5 bp and then re-mapped.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This process is repeated till all reads uniquely map, or till the reads are extended to their entirety.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Only paired end reads with each side uniquely mapped to a single genomic loci are kept.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] All other paired end reads are discarded.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] With increased read length, more recent pipelines (e.g.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Juicer and the 4D-Nucleosome Data Portal) often align short Hi-C reads with an alignment algorithm capable of chimeric alignment, such as bwa-mem, chromap and dragmap.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This procedure calls alignment once and is simpler than iterative mapping.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The mapped reads are then each assigned a single genomic alignment location according to its 5' mapped position in the genome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] For each read pair, a location is assigned to only one of the restriction fragments, thus should fall in close proximity to a restriction site and less than the maximum molecule length away.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Reads mapped more than the maximum molecule length away from the closest restriction sites are the results of physical breakage of the chromatin or non-canonical nuclease activities.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Because these reads also instruct information on chromatin interactions, they are not discarded, but appropriate filtering must take place after assigning genomic locations to remove technical noise in the dataset.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Depending on whether the read pair falls within the same or different restriction fragments, different filtering criteria are applied.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] If the paired reads map to the same restriction fragment, they likely represent un-ligated dangling ends or circularized fragments that are uninformative, and are therefore removed from the dataset.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] These reads could also represent PCR artifacts, undigested chromatin fragments, or simply, reads with low alignment quality.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Whatever their origin, reads mapped to the same fragment are considered "spurious signals" and are typically discarded before downstream processing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The remaining paired reads mapped to distinct restriction fragments are also filtered to discard identical/redundant PCR products, and this is achieved by removing reads sharing the exact same sequence or 5' alignment positions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Additional levels of filtering could also be applied to fit the experimental purpose.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] For example, potential undigested restriction sites could be specifically filtered out, rather than passively identified, by removing reads mapped to the same chromosomal strand with a small distance (user-defined, experience-based) in between.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Based on their midpoint coordinates, Hi-C restriction fragments are binned into fixed genomic intervals, with bin sizes ranging from 40 kb to 1 Mb.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Bin to bin interactions are aggregated by simply taking the sum, although more focused and informative methods have also been developed over the years to further enhance the signal.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] One such method described by Rao et al. aims to push the limit of bin size to smaller and smaller bins, eventually having > 80% of bins covered by 1000 reads each, which significantly increased the resolution of the final analysis results.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Bin-level filtering, just like fragment-level filtering, also takes place to shed experimental artifacts from the obtained data.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Bins with high noise and low signals are removed as they typically represent highly repetitive genomic contents around the telomeres and centromeres.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This is done by comparing the individual bin sums to the sum of all bins and removing the bottom 1% of bins, or by using the variance as a measure of noise.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Low-coverage bins, or bins three standard deviations below the center of a log-normal distribution (which fits the total number of contacts per genomic bin), are removed using the MAD-max (maximum allowed median absolute deviation) filter.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] After binning, Hi-C data will be stored in a symmetrical matrix format.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] More recently, many approaches have been proposed to predetermine the optimal bin size for different Hi-C experiments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Li et al. in 2018 described deDoc, a method where bin size is selected as the one at which the structural entropy of the Hi-C matrix reaches a stable minimum.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] QuASAR, on the other hand, offers a bit more quality assessment, and compares replicate scores of the samples (given that replicates are indeed included for the experimental purpose) to find the maximum usable resolution.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Some publications also tried to score interaction frequencies at the single-fragment level, where a higher coverage can be achieved even with a lower number of reads.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] HiCPlus, a tool developed by Zhang et al. in 2018, is able to impute Hi-C matrices similar to the original ones using only 1/16 of the original reads.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Balancing refers to the process of bias correction of the obtained Hi-C data, and can be either explicit or implicit.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Explicit balancing methods require the explicit definitions of biases known to be associated with Hi-C reads (or any high-throughput sequencing technique in general) including the read mappability, GC content, as well as individual fragment length.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] A correction factor is first computed for each of the considered biases, followed by each of their combination, and then applied to the read counts per genomic bin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] However, some biases can come from an unknown origin, in which case an implicit balancing approach is used instead.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Implicit balancing relies on the assumption that each genomic locus should have "equal visibility", which suggests that the interaction signal at each genomic locus in the Hi-C data should add up to the same total amount.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] One approach called iterative correction uses the Sinkhorn–Knopp balancing algorithm and attempts to balance the symmetrical matrix using the aforementioned assumption (by equalizing the sum of each and every row and column in the matrix).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The algorithm iteratively alternates between two steps: 1) dividing each row by its mean, and 2) dividing each column by its mean, which are guaranteed to converge in the end and leave no obviously high rows or columns in the interaction matrix.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Other computational methods also exist to normalize the biases inherent to Hi-C data, including sequential component normalization (SCN), the Knight-Ruiz matrix-balancing approach, and eigenvector decomposition (ICE) normalization.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In the end, both the explicit and the implicit bias correction methods yield comparable results.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Cis/trans interactions are one of the two strongest interaction patterns observed in Hi-C maps.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] They are not locus-specific, and thus are considered as a genome-level pattern.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Typically, a higher interaction frequency is observed, on average, for pairs of loci residing on the same chromosome (in cis) than pairs of loci residing on different chromosomes (in trans).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In Hi-C interaction matrices, cis/trans interactions appear as square blocks centered along a diagonal, matching individual chromosomes at the same time.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Because this pattern is relatively consistent across different species and cell types, it can be used to assess the quality of the data.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This pattern refers to the distance-dependent decay of interaction frequencies on a genome level, and represents the second one of the two strongest Hi-C interaction patterns.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] As the interaction frequencies between cis-interacting loci decrease (as a result of further distance between them), a gradual decrease of interaction frequency can be observed moving away from the diagonal in the interaction matrix.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Various polymer models exist to statistically characterize the properties of loci pairs separated by a given distance, but discrete binning and fitting continuous functions are two common ways to analyze the distance-dependent interaction frequencies between datapoints.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] First, interaction frequencies can be binned based on their genomic distance, then a continuous function is fitted to the data using information of the average of each bin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The resulting decay function is plotted on a log-log plot so that a linear line can be used to represent the power-law decays predicted by polymer models.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This pattern can be found at both high and low frequencies.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Because chromosomes consist of two types of genomic regions that alternate along the length of individual chromosomes, the interaction frequencies between two regions of the same type and interaction frequencies between two regions of different types can be quite different.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The definition of the active (A) and inactive (B) chromatin compartments is based on principal component analysis, first established by Lieberman-Aiden et al. in 2009.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Their approach calculated the correlation of the Hi-C matrix of observed vs. expected signal (obtained from a distance-normalized contact matrix) ratio, and used the sign of the first eigenvector to denote positive and negative parts of the resulting plot as A and B compartments, respectively.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Many genomic studies have indicated that chromatin compartments are correlated with chromatin states, such as gene density, DNA accessibility, GC content, replication timing, and histone marks.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Therefore, type A compartments are more specifically defined to represent the gene-dense regions of euchromatin, while type B compartments represent heterochromatic regions with less gene activities.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Overall, chromatin compartments offer insights on the general organization principles of the genome of interest.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] More and more bioinformatics tools capable of performing compartment calling have been developed over the past decade, including HOMER, HiTC R, and CscoreTool.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Although they each has their own differences and optimizations made on the original 2009 approach, their base protocols still rely on principal component analysis.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] TADs are sub-Mb structures that may harbor gene-regulatory features, such as local promoter-enhancer interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] More generally, TADs are considered as an emergent property of underlying biological mechanisms, which defines TADs as loop extrusions, compartmentalizations, or any dynamic genomic pattern rather than a static structural feature of the genome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Thus, TADs represent regulatory microenvironments and usually show up on a Hi-C map as blocks of highly self-interacting regions in which interaction frequencies within the region are significantly higher than interaction frequencies between two adjacent regions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In Hi-C interaction matrices, TADs are square blocks of elevated interaction frequencies centred along the diagonal.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] However, this is merely an oversimplified description, and identifying the actual pattern requires much more statistical processing and estimation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] One approach to identify TADs was described by Dixon et al., where they first calculated (within some genomic range) the difference between the average upstream interactions and the average downstream interactions of each bin in the matrix.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This difference was then transformed into a chi-squared statistic based on the Hidden Markov Model, and any sharp change in this chi-squared value, called the directionality index, will define the boundaries of TADs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Alternatively, one could simply take the ratio between average upstream and downstream interactions to define TAD boundaries, as did Naumova et al.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Another approach is to calculate the average interaction frequencies crossing over each bin, again within some predetermined genomic range.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The resulting value is referred to as the insulation score and can be thought of as the average of a square sliding along the diagonal of the matrix (Crane et al.).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] This value is expected to be lower at TAD boundaries; thus, one can use standard statistical techniques to find local minima (boundaries), and define regions between consecutive boundaries to be TADs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] However, as is increasingly recognized today, TADs represent a hierarchical series of structures that cannot be fully characterized by one-dimensional scores given by the previous methods.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The increased resolution available in newer datasets can now explicitly address TADs with multiscale analysis approaches.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] As first introduced by Armatus, resolution specific domains can be identified and a consensus set of domains conserved across resolutions can be calculated, which transforms the problem of TAD calling into the optimization of scoring functions based on their local interaction densities.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Variations of this approach with different objective functions, such as Lavaburst, MrTADFinder, 3DNetMod, and Matryoshka, are also developed to achieve better computing performance on higher resolution datasets.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Biologically, regulatory interactions usually occur at much smaller scale than TADs, and two genomic elements can activate/inhibit the expression of a gene within as small a distance as 1 kb.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Therefore, point interactions are important in interpreting Hi-C maps, and are expected to appear as local enrichments in contact probability.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] However, current methodologies for the identification of point interactions are all implicit in nature, in that they do not instruct what a point interaction should look like.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Instead, point mutations are identified as outliers with higher interaction frequencies than expected within the Hi-C matrix, given that the background model consists only of the strongest signals such as the distance-decay functions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] The background model can be estimated and constructed using both local signal distributions and global approaches (i.e. chromosome-wide/genome-wide).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] Many of the aforementioned bioinformatics packages incorporate algorithms to identify point interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] In short, the significance of individual pairwise interaction is calculated, and significantly high outliers are corrected for multiple testing before they are recognized as truly informative point interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p01] It is helpful to compliment identified point interactions with additional evidence such as analysis of enrichment scores and biological replicates, to indicate that these interactions are indeed of biological significance.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Hi-C has been primarily used to study chromatin folding.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] These studies have revealed that the principles of chromosome organization are conserved across cell types and species.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Hi-C is also used in genome assembly, where long-range contact frequencies between sequences in a draft assembly are used to group, order, and orient them into chromosome-scale assemblies.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Hi-C can also be used to detect structural variations in the genome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Hi-C can reveal chromatin conformation changes during cell division.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] In interphase, chromatins are generally loose and vivacious so that transcription regulation and other regulatory activities could take place.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] When entering mitosis and cell division, chromatins become compactly folded into dense cylindrical chromosomes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] When mitotic division is completed and the cell re-enters the interphase, chromatin 3D structures are observed to be re-established, and transcription regulation is restored.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Standard Hi-C can be used to investigate this research question.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] In 2015, Dixon et al. applied standard Hi-C to capture global 3D dynamics in human ESCs during their differentiation into high five cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Since then, Hi-C has been recognized as one of the standard methods to probe for transcriptional regulatory activities, and has confirmed that chromosome architecture is closely related to cell fate.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Mammalian somatic growth and development starts with the fertilization of sperm and oocyte, followed by the zygote stage, the 2-cell, 4-cell, and the 8-cell stage, the blastocyst stage, and finally the embryo stage.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Hi-C made it possible to explore the comprehensive genomic architecture during growth and development, as both sis-Hi-C and in situ Hi-C have reported that TADs and genomic A and B compartments are not obviously present and appear to be less well-structured in oocyte cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] These structural features of the chromatin only gradually establish from weaker frequencies to cleaner and more frequent datapoints after fertilization, as developmental stages progress.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] As data on 3D genome structures becomes more and more prevalent in recent years, Hi-C begins to be used as a means to track evolutionary structural features/changes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Genomic single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) and TADs are typically conserved across species, along with the CTCF factor in the chromatin domain evolution.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Other factors, however, have been revealed by Hi-C techniques to experience structural evolutions in 3D architecture.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] These include codon usage frequency similarity (CUFS), paralog gene co-regulation, and spatially co-evolving orthologous modules (SCOMs).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] For large-scale domain evolution, chromosomal translocations, syntenic regions, as well as genomic rearrangement regions were all relatively conserved.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] These findings imply that Hi-C technologies is capable of providing an alternative point of view in the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Several studies have employed the use of Hi-C to describe and study chromatin architecture in different cancers and their impact on disease pathogenesis.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Kloetgen et al. used in situ Hi-C to study T cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (T-ALL) and found a TAD fusion event that removed a CTCF insulation site, allowing for the oncogene MYC's promoter to directly interact with a distal super enhancer.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Fang et al. have also shown how there are T-ALL specific gain or loss of chromatin insulation, which alters the strength of TAD architecture of the genome, using in situ Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Low-C has been used to map the chromatin structure of primary B cells of a diffuse large B-cell lymphoma patient and was used to find high chromosome structural variation between the patient and healthy B-cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] Overall, the application of Hi-C and its variants in cancer research provides unique insight into the molecular underpinnings of the driving factors of cell abnormality.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/hi-c-genomic-analysis-technique-p02] It can help explain biological phenomena (high MYC expression in T-ALL) and help aid drug development to target mechanisms unique to cancerous cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] The organization of DNA presents a remarkable biological challenge: human DNA can reach 2 meters and is packed into the nucleus with the diameter of 5-20 μm.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] At the same time, the critical cell processes involve complex processes on highly compacted DNA, such as transcription, replication, recombination, DNA repair, and cell division.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Loop extrusion is a key mechanism that organizes DNA into loops, enabling its efficient compaction and functional organization.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] For instance, *in vitro* experiments show that cohesin can compact DNA by 80%, while condensin achieves a remarkable 10,000-fold compaction of mitotic chromosomes, as evidenced by microscopy, Hi-C, and polymer simulations.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Another challenge lies in establishing long-range genomic communication, which can span hundreds of thousands of base pairs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Physical encounters between genomic elements are intrinsically random and promiscuous without mechanisms to facilitate them.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Loop extrusion has been proposed to provide an effective solution to regulate contacts by bringing target elements into proximity while limiting contact with unwanted loci.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Loop extrusion is performed by the SMC family of protein-complexes which includes cohesin, condensin, and SMC5/6 each playing specialized roles depending on the organism, cell cycle phase, and biological context.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Cohesin mediates chromatin loop formation and stabilization, particularly during interphase in vertebrates, where it facilitates transcriptional regulation by promoting distal enhancer-promoter interactions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] During mitosis and meiosis, cohesin dissociates from chromosome arms ceding its loop extrusion role to condensin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Loop extrusion by condensin mediates large-scale chromosome compaction, creating the compact, rod-like chromosome structures required for accurate segregation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Unlike cohesin and condensin, SMC5/6 is a loop extruding factor which primarily functions in maintaining genome integrity during DNA damage repair and resolving replication stress.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Despite their distinct roles, SMC complexes share a highly conserved ring-like structure.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Two SMC proteins (usually, SMC1 and SMC3) are connected via a hinge region and linked at their heads by a kleisin subunit, forming a closed ring.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] These two SMC proteins have ATPase domains at their heads, which bind together and hydrolyze ATP.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Cycles of ATP binding and hydrolysis mediate conformational changes in the ring structure, driving DNA translocation and stepwise loop extrusion.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] ATP is essential for both initiating loop extrusion (e.g., loading SMC complexes onto DNA) and propagating it (growing loops by translocating along DNA).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] The tension within the DNA significantly influences extrusion efficiency.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] At low tension, SMC complexes can make larger loop-capture steps, while higher tension can lead to stalling or reversal of loop extrusion.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] The dynamic nature of loop extrusion is tightly controlled by accessory factors and post-translational modifications, especially in the case of cohesin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] In vertebrates, NIPBL (and orthologs like Mau2 in yeast or SCC2 and SCC4) is crucial for loading SMC complexes onto DNA, initiating and maintaining active extrusion.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] PDS5 is thought to pause the extrusion process.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] The SMC can then either restart extruding or be unloaded by the additional binding of WAPL, which ensure proper recycling and turnover.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Post-translational modifications also play a key role.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Acetylation of cohesin by enzymes such as ESCO1 and ESCO2 stabilizes chromatin loops, particularly at CTCF-bound sites.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Similarly, SUMOylation, mediated by the NSE2 subunit of the SMC5/6 complex, enhances the recruitment of SMC5/6 to sites of DNA damage, supporting its role in genomic stability.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Loop extruders can encounter various obstacles while extruding.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] For example, many of which were shown to directly interact with cohesin and hypothesized to stop its movement on DNA.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] However, *in vivo* experiments demonstrate that cohesin can frequently bypass obstacles larger than its ring size.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] **CTCF:** The C-terminal DNA-binding domain of CTCF has been shown to directly interact with SA2 and SCC1 subunits of cohesin to stop extrusion and retain it on DNA with recent evidence suggesting a tension-dependence to the interaction.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] CTCF stalls cohesin in a highly directional manner where cohesin can bypass CTCF in one orientation but stalls when encountering it in the opposite orientation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] This directionality allows for the creation of isolated domains on the genome called Topologically Associating Domains (TADs) which have been proposed to have a large role in gene-regulation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] **RNA polymerase/transcription**: Transcribing polymerases can serve as barriers to cohesin that may not only stall extruders but also act as a motor pushing cohesin in the direction of polymerase movement.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] The size of a polymerase with an RNA transcript is usually larger than the size of the cohesin ring, and the stall force of cohesin is much smaller than that of polymerase, allowing for effective barrier function by polymerase.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Furthermore, it has been found that RNA can directly interact with cohesin subunits.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] **DNA replication:** Replication forks and replisomes have been shown to restrict loop extrusion activity.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Additionally, the MCM helicase, which is associated with origins of replication, has been found to counteract the extrusion of cohesin on DNA.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] **R-loops**: Some evidence suggests that R-loops can also act as barriers to loop extrusion, and R-loops have been shown to interact with cohesin subunits.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] However, other evidence suggests that R-loops may instead act as cohesin loaders.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] The first direct evidence of loop extrusion came from in vitro imaging studies on fluorescently labeled DNA with condensin or cohesin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Extrusion was found to be ATP-dependent and happened at ~1-3kb/s.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] The stall force was measured to be around 0.1-1pN which is small compared to other molecular motors.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Loop extrusion by the SMC complex cohesin was suggested on the basis of chromatin contact maps from Hi-C experiments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] These maps displayed genomic domains of self-contact of a few hundred kb in size, referred to as topologically associating domains (TADs).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] These domains are generally bordered by binding sites for the CTCF protein, which are oriented in a convergent manner such that CTCF proteins "point" toward each other.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Subsequent quantitative simulation models proposing loop extrusion by cohesin were able to reproduce patterns of chromatin contacts observed in Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] More recent evidence comes from imaging of chromatin dynamics in the presence and absence of cohesin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Experiments with fluorescently tagged genomic loci analyzed by mathematical inference techniques indicate that these loci into come into spatial proximity more frequently in the presence of cohesin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Associated simulation modeling again indicates that chromatin loop extrusion can explain these observations.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Most work on the biological role of loop extrusion relies on inhibiting loop extruders and observing the consequences.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Depletion of cohesin leads to the disappearance of TADs and some loss in transcription genome-wide.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] In more specific settings, inhibition of cohesin has been found to inhibit neuronal maturation and differentiation and function of dendritic cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Depletion of either condensin I or condensin II at the entry into mitosis leads to abnormal chromosome formation and improper segregation of sister chromatids.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Loop extrusion has been found across the tree of life with suggested roles in immune response, DNA repair, enhancer-promoter interactions, and mitosis.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/loop-extrusion] Since the exact modalities of LEF dynamics remain uncertain, these models provide a flexible framework to explore different hypothetical behaviors of LEFs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] At the smallest scale, DNA is packaged into units called nucleosomes, which compact DNA about 7-fold.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] In addition, nucleosomes protect DNA from damage and carry epigenetic information.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Positions of nucleosomes determine accessibility of DNA to transcription factors.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] At the intermediate scale, DNA looping can physically bring together DNA elements that would otherwise be separated by large distances.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] These interactions allow regulatory signals to cross over large genomic distances—for example, from enhancers to promoters.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] At a larger scale, chromosomes are organized into two compartments labelled A ("active") and B ("inactive"), which are further subdivided into sub-compartments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] At the largest scale, entire chromosomes segregate into distinct regions called chromosome territories.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Chromosome organization is dynamically-maintained at all scales.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Individual nucleosomes undergo constant thermal motion and nucleosome breathing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] At intermediate scales, an active process of loop extrusion creates dynamic loops and Topologically Associating Domains (TADs).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Each human cell contains around two metres of DNA, which must be tightly folded to fit inside the cell nucleus.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] However, in order for the cell to function, proteins must be able to access the sequence information contained within the DNA, in spite of its tightly-packed nature.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Hence, the cell has a number of mechanisms in place to control how DNA is organized.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Moreover, nuclear organization can play a role in establishing cell identity.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Cells within an organism have near identical nucleic acid sequences, but often exhibit different phenotypes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] One way in which this individuality occurs is through changes in genome architecture, which can alter the expression of different sets of genes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] These alterations can have a downstream effect on cellular functions such as cell cycle facilitation, DNA replication, nuclear transport, and alteration of nuclear structure.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Controlled changes in nuclear organization are essential for proper cellular function.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The organization of chromosomes into distinct regions within the nucleus was first proposed in 1885 by Carl Rabl.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Later in 1909, with the help of the microscopy technology at the time, Theodor Boveri coined the termed chromosome territories after observing that chromosomes occupy individually distinct nuclear regions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Since then, mapping genome architecture has become a major topic of interest.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Over the last ten years, rapid methodological developments have greatly advanced understanding in this field.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Large-scale DNA organization can be assessed with DNA imaging using fluorescent tags, such as DNA Fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH), and specialized microscopes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Additionally, high-throughput sequencing technologies such as Chromosome Conformation Capture-based methods can measure how often DNA regions are in close proximity.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] At the same time, progress in genome-editing techniques (such as CRISPR/Cas9, ZFNs, and TALENs) have made it easier to test the organizational function of specific DNA regions and proteins.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] There is also growing interest in the rheological properties of the interchromosomal space, studied by the means of Fluorescence Correlation Spectroscopy and its variants.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Architectural proteins regulate chromatin structure by establishing physical interactions between DNA elements.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] These proteins tend to be highly conserved across a majority of eukaryotic species.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The organization of DNA within the nucleus begins with the 10 nm fiber, a "beads-on-a-string" structure made of nucleosomes connected by 20-60bp linkers.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] A fiber of nucleosomes is interrupted by regions of accessible DNA, which are 100-1000bp long regions devoid of nucleosomes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Transcription factors bind within accessible DNA to displace nucleosomes and form cis-regulatory elements.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Sites of accessible DNA are typically probed by ATAC-seq or DNase-Seq experimental methods.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] A 30 nm fiber has long been proposed as the next layer of chromatin organization.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] While 30 nm fiber is often visible in vitro under high salt concentration, its existence in vivo has been questioned in many recent studies.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Instead, these studies point towards a disordered fiber with a width of 20 to 50 nm.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The process of loop extrusion by SMC complexes dynamically creates chromatin loops ranging in size from 50-100kb in yeast to up to several Mb in mammals.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] There is strong support for loop extrusion in yeast, mammals, and nematodes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] In mammals, loop extrusion is responsible for the formation of topologically associating domains and loops between CTCF sites, as well as for bringing promoters and enhancers together.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] CTCF sites serve as boundaries of insulated neighborhoods or topologically associating domains.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The presence of loop extrusion in fruit flies is debated and the formation of DNA loops may be mediated by a different process of boundary element pairing.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Self-interacting (or self-associating) domains are found in many organisms.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] In eukaryotes, they have been usually referred to as TADs irrespective of the mechanism of their formation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] TADs have a higher ratio of chromosomal contacts within the domain than outside it.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] They are formed through the help of architectural proteins.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] In many organisms, TADs correlate with regulation of gene expression, and enhancers and promoters within a TAD interact at higher frequency.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Lamina-associating domains (LADs) and nucleolar-associating domains (NADs) are regions of the chromosome that interact with the nuclear lamina and nucleolus, respectively.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Making up approximately 40% of the genome, LADs consist mostly of gene poor regions and span between 40kb to 30Mb in size.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] There are two known types of LADs: constitutive LADs (cLADs) and facultative LADs (fLADs). cLADs are A-T rich heterochromatin regions that remain on lamina and are seen across many types of cells and species.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] There is evidence that these regions are important to the structural formation of interphase chromosome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] On the other hand, fLADs have varying lamina interactions and contain genes that are either activated or repressed between individual cells indicating cell-type specificity.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The boundaries of LADs, like self-interacting domains, are enriched in transcriptional elements and architectural protein binding sites.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] NADs, which constitutes 4% of the genome, share nearly all of the same physical characteristics as LADs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] In fact, DNA analysis of these two types of domains have shown that many sequences overlap, indicating that certain regions may switch between lamina-binding and nucleolus-binding.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] NADs are associated with nucleolus function.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The nucleolus is the largest sub-organelle within the nucleus and is the principal site for rRNA transcription.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] It also acts in signal recognition particle biosynthesis, protein sequestration, and viral replication.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The nucleolus forms around rDNA genes from different chromosomes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] However, only a subset of rDNA genes is transcribed at a time and do so by looping into the interior of the nucleolus.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The rest of the genes lay on the periphery of the sub-nuclear organelle in silenced heterochromatin state.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] A/B compartments were first discovered in early Hi-C studies.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Researchers noticed that the whole genome could be split into two spatial compartments, labelled "A" and "B", where regions in compartment A tend to interact preferentially with A compartment-associated regions than B compartment-associated ones.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Similarly, regions in compartment B tend to associate with other B compartment-associated regions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] A/B compartment interactions span larger genomic regions than TADs and LADs and represent a network connecting regions of open and expression-active chromatin ("A" compartments) or closed and expression-inactive chromatin ("B" compartments).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Generally compartments represent large domains of chromatin, but the genomic compartmentalization is visible also at a very fine level, with examples of single genes alternating between A and B compartment.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] A compartments tend to be gene-rich, have high GC-content, contain histone markers for active transcription, and usually displace the interior of the nucleus.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] As well, they are typically made up of self-interacting domains and contain early replication origins.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] B compartments, on the other hand, tend to be gene-poor, compact, contain histone markers for gene silencing, and lie on the nuclear periphery.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] They consist mostly of LADs and contain late replication origins.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] In addition, higher resolution Hi-C coupled with machine learning methods has revealed that A/B compartments can be refined into subcompartments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The fact that compartments self-interact is consistent with the idea that the nucleus localizes proteins and other factors such as long non-coding RNA (lncRNA) in regions suited for their individual roles.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] An example of this is the presence of multiple transcription factories throughout the nuclear interior.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] These factories are associated with elevated levels of transcription due to the high concentration of transcription factors (such as transcription protein machinery, active genes, regulatory elements, and nascent RNA).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Around 95% of active genes are transcribed within transcription factories.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Each factory can transcribe multiple genes – these genes need not have similar product functions, nor do they need to lie on the same chromosome.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Finally, the co-localization of genes within transcription factories is known to depend on cell type.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The last level of organization concerns the distinct positioning of individual chromosomes within the nucleus.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The region occupied by a chromosome is called a chromosome territory (CT).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Among eukaryotes, CTs have several common properties.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] First, although chromosomal locations are not the same across cells within a population, there is some preference among individual chromosomes for particular regions.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] For example, large, gene-poor chromosomes are commonly located on the periphery near the nuclear lamina while smaller, gene-rich chromosomes group closer to the center of the nucleus.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Second, individual chromosome preference is variable among different cell types.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] For example, the X-chromosome has shown to localize to the periphery more often in liver cells than in kidney cells.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] Another conserved property of chromosome territories is that homologous chromosomes tend to be far apart from one another during cell interphase.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The final characteristic is that the position of individual chromosomes during each cell cycle stays relatively the same until the start of mitosis.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/nuclear-organization] The mechanisms and reasons behind chromosome territory characteristics is still unknown and further experimentation is needed.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] A **topologically associating domain** (TAD) is a self-interacting genomic region, meaning that DNA sequences within a TAD physically interact with each other more frequently than with sequences outside the TAD.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] The average size of a topologically associating domain (TAD) is 1000 kb in humans, 880 kb in mouse cells, and 140 kb in fruit flies.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Boundaries at both side of these domains are conserved between different mammalian cell types and even across species and are highly enriched with CCCTC-binding factor (CTCF) and cohesin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] In addition, some types of genes (such as transfer RNA genes and housekeeping genes) appear near TAD boundaries more often than would be expected by chance.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] The functions of TADs are not fully understood and are still a matter of debate.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Most of the studies indicate TADs regulate gene expression by limiting the enhancer-promoter interaction to each TAD; however, a recent study uncouples TAD organization and gene expression.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Disruption of TAD boundaries are found to be associated with wide range of diseases such as cancer, variety of limb malformations such as synpolydactyly, Cooks syndrome, and F-syndrome, and number of brain disorders like Hypoplastic corpus callosum and Adult-onset demyelinating leukodystrophy.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Furthermore, studies have revealed that interactions between promoters and enhancers spanning single or multiple TADs, are fundamental to the exact dynamics of gene expression.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] The genomic elements underlying these interactions are named distal tethering elements (DTEs) and it has been shown that these elements are important for precise gene activation of Hox genes in early embryogenesis of *D. melanogaster*.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] The mechanisms underlying TAD formation are also complex and not yet fully elucidated, though a number of protein complexes and DNA elements are associated with TAD boundaries.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] However, the handcuff model and the loop extrusion model describe the TAD formation by the aid of CTCF and cohesin proteins.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Furthermore, it has been proposed that the stiffness of TAD boundaries itself could cause the domain insulation and TAD formation.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] A typical TAD boundary contains a cluster of CTCF sites which may act synergistically to create a region with distinct properties of the nucleosome fiber that separates two neighboring TADs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] TADs are defined as regions whose DNA sequences preferentially contact each other.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] They were discovered in 2012 using chromosome conformation capture techniques including Hi-C.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] They have been shown to be present in multiple species, including fruit flies (Drosophila), mouse, plants, fungi and human genomes.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] In bacteria, they are referred to as Chromosomal Interacting Domains (CIDs).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] TAD locations are defined by applying an algorithm to Hi-C data.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] For example, TADs are often called according to the so-called "directionality index".
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] The directionality index is calculated for individual 40kb bins, by collecting the reads that fall in the bin, and observing whether their paired reads map upstream or downstream of the bin (read pairs are required to span no more than 2Mb).
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] A positive value indicates that more read pairs lie downstream than upstream, and a negative value indicates the reverse.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Mathematically, the directionality index is a signed chi-square statistic.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] The development of specialized genome browsers and visualization tools such as Juicebox, HiGlass/HiPiler, The 3D Genome Browser, 3DIV, 3D-GNOME, and TADKB have enabled us to visualize the TAD organization of regions of interest in different cell types.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] A number of proteins are known to be associated with TAD formation including the protein CTCF (usually several CTCF binding sites are present at a TAD boundary) and the protein complex cohesin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] It is also unknown what components are required at TAD boundaries; however, in mammalian cells, it has been shown that these boundary regions have comparatively high levels of CTCF binding.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Computer simulations have shown that chromatin loop extrusion driven by cohesin motors can generate TADs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] In the loop extrusion model, cohesin binds chromatin, pulls it in, and extrudes chromatin to progressively grow a loop.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Chromatin on both sides of the cohesin complex is extruded until cohesin encounters a chromatin-bound CTCF protein, typically located at the boundary of a TAD.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] In this way, TAD boundaries can be brought together as the anchors of a chromatin loop.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Indeed, in vitro, cohesin has been observed to processively extrude DNA loops in an ATP-dependent manner and stall at CTCF.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] However, some in vitro data indicates that the observed loops may be artifacts.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Importantly, since cohesins can dynamically unbind from chromatin, this model suggests that TADs (and associated chromatin loops) are dynamic, transient structures, in agreement with in vivo observations.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Other mechanisms for TAD formation have been suggested.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] For example, some simulations suggest that transcription-generated supercoiling can relocalize cohesin to TAD boundaries or that passively diffusing cohesin "slip links" can generate TADs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] TADs have been reported to be relatively constant between different cell types (in stem cells and blood cells, for example), and even between species in specific cases.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Comparative TAD analysis between *Drosophila melanogaster* and *Drosophila subobscura*, with a divergence time of approximately 49 million years, has revealed a conservation in range of 30-40%.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] The majority of observed interactions between promoters and enhancers do not cross TAD boundaries.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Removing a TAD boundary (for example, using CRISPR to delete the relevant region of the genome) can allow new promoter-enhancer contacts to form.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] This can affect gene expression nearby - such misregulation has been shown to cause limb malformations (e.g. polydactyly) in humans and mice.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Computer simulations have shown that transcription-induced supercoiling of chromatin fibres can explain how TADs are formed and how they can assure very efficient interactions between enhancers and their cognate promoters located in the same TAD.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Replication timing domains have been shown to be associated with TADs as their boundary is co localized with the boundaries of TADs that are located at either sides of compartments.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Insulated neighborhoods, DNA loops formed by CTCF/cohesin-bound regions, are proposed to functionally underlie TADs.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Genome rearrangement breakpoint have shown to be enriched at the TAD boundaries in *D. melanogaster*.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Disruption of TAD boundaries can affect the expression of nearby genes, and this can cause disease.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] For example, genomic structural variants that disrupt TAD boundaries have been reported to cause developmental disorders such as human limb malformations.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Additionally, several studies have provided evidence that the disruption or rearrangement of TAD boundaries can provide growth advantages to certain cancers, such as T-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (T-ALL), gliomas, and lung cancer.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] Lamina-associated domains (LADs) are parts of the chromatin that heavily interact with the lamina, a network-like structure at the inner membrane of the nucleus.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] LADs consist mostly of transcriptionally silent chromatin, being enriched with trimethylated Lys27 on histone H3, (i.e.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] H3K27me3); which is a common posttranslational histone modification of heterochromatin.
[src:hi-c-chromatin/topologically-associating-domain] LADs have CTCF-binding sites at their periphery.
